Detection_Notes: YBCU found in sycamore on north side of drainage. contact called once, flew West out of sight on north end, called again, then flew on south end drainage to another sycamore. Then flew south out of sight.

SurveyPt_Notes: Mexican Jays present- waited to call playback
lack of overstoy begins- exposed area

Survey_Notes: Coopers hawk at points 11, 13, and 15. Stopped calls early, hawk stayed in area though, so survey stopped/discontinued
Very Dry; GAQU, SCOR, CACW, ATFL, BGGN, VERD, GRRO, BTSP, BHCO, WWOO, HOFI, BCHU, BUSH, CBTH, GIWO, NOCA, RTHA, BEWR, CATO, LBWD, BEVI, PHAN, BCFL
very quiet. few birds. dry. LBWO, CACW, GAQU, LHSH, GIWO, CBTH, WOTA, GRRO, BTSP, CATO, TUVU, COHA, CRTH, BEVI, COR
Very dry country. Humid morning-oppresive. many cows.
Very dry. Saturated soil and minimal surface water exist only at spring near route's western end.
speaker is dead. Using new playback from digital player; volume OK. flow 1 ft/ac in the stream
CP's 11-15 inaccessible due to high and fast water and noise level of water running
encountered a swarm of bees at cottonwood puddle. retreated! ~ 200m from bees filled the narrow drainage. Yikes! Very dry. Habitat not suitable for YBCU. Only 1 mud puddle.
bees in drainage. only one large cottonwood; other than that, no riparian veg or birds. note that the drainage is very steep and narrow. not suitable for YBCU even at spring. loud buzzing.
very dry. saturated soil and minimal surface water exist only at spring near route's western end.

SurveyPt_Notes: no calls played. 3 coo heard over 15min. spent another 45min around spot 4- heard two birds in contact  one making low kowlp , other answering coo

Survey_Notes: Skipped CPs 8-11 due to the presence of ravens (5) and grey hawk (3) and coopers hawk (1)
first time surveying this area to cover mining zone. start: no cloud cover, but smoke overcast from west coast fires.

SurveyPt_Notes: stopped early due to coopers presence

NumKowlp: battery died in player. bird vocalized unsolicited from 50m upstream. one contact call. same area as last year.

Detection_Notes: bird responsed to 2nd playback. coming from near mount of larry canyon. as I was leaving call point, bird called twice more
bird responded enthusiastically to first playback . contact call with purr; calling from canyon for about 4min
pair of birds; 6 responded to tape and 7 immediately answered from tree above me. 7 looked at me then dipped into cottonwood.
ird responded after call point concluded and I was moving to next spot
responded after 2nd call and flew overhead
contact call heard from upstream. not sure if it's #2 or new bird
bird answered first call from upstream
bird called while I was setting up
responded after 5th call downstream
responded to D2 from upstream
weird raspy calls. not bright white below. no spots on tail.

Survey_Notes: on the way out, cuckoos were calling and flying every 100-200m

NumKowlp: within 50m of estimated bird from detection 1

Survey_Notes: dead cow on hike. appeared to have been head shot ` 300m upstream of ranch fresh ATV tracks nearby. dead les than 24hr
trees heavily stressed: willows 50% leaf loss, cottonwoods 25% leaf loss

Detection_Notes: heard faintly 3x; very very faint and far away
surely, detection 1 and 2 are the same bird. rare tent caterpillar noted
heard four kowlps. This location was about 300m downstream of our usual end point for the transect. I was setting up to do one last callpoint where I heard it call spontaneously.
potentially same cuckoo as 1 in 40ft cottonwood

Survey_Notes: squishy cowpies and cattle tracks in river channel and banks. several trees fell over. cattle have munched cattails and sedges at this location

Detection_Notes: Water noted flowing

Survey_Notes: recent rain; the creek is flowing at the start

SurveyPt_Notes: water flowing and disappears into sand

Detection_Notes: two alarm calls downstreams before start of playback

At 6:31 two YBCU flew from the noted location to the tree noted in Detection #1. No one saw a YBCU fly from the Detection #1 location to the Detection #2 location, so there could have been 3 YBCU. To be conservative, only two birds are counted for this callpoint.

NumKowlp: called from large SAGO before flying downstream to a mesquite

Detection_Notes: on hike back to truck
responded from upstream
very faint KUK calls 200m upstream. Walked 110m upstream and was about to play call when we heard bird downstream again. Walked short distance downstream. Bird by road in oak.
heard before beginning of survey. possible nest exchange vocalization
did not finish broadcast (and survey) due to hawk presence
contact call with knocks, but not alarm knocks

NumKowlp: birds #1 still cooing, may be following us

SurveyPt_Notes: survey route changed slightly from previous years due to flooding
survey stopped due to river flow

Survey_Notes: very wet, lots of rain in previous days

incubating

Flew from direction of #2
Pair - 2 flew by, one carrying nesting material
Speaker not working well.

On 5th call YBCU came in from NW. Landed in tree on west side for great views. Flew around us to east side about 20m away and started cooing. 2nd YBCU heard CON call from west, never seen. 1st bird coo-ed constantly for 10 minutes
COOing but stopped when we did play back. Heard COO call from east after P4 and continued to call for long time
Likely same bird as above
YBCU flew into tree that had CBTH and made COO call. Flew west and made CON call
Lots of water. YBCU called after P1. Perched in mesquite and stayed put for 7 minutes.
Called first with quiet knocking.
Got CLOSER OBSERVATION AT 499778/3472870
Possibly 2 birds right at audio recorder.
Heard then both seen and heard. Crossed road and called at least 3 times.
Bird called and flew towards us. Was very intently looking around, pecked on bare twig with wings held down at sides in a very aggressive manner.
Flew in from other side of road, called once but looked around intently
No cicadas buzzing, no grasshoppers, lots of cricket sounds.
Now stream has running water (none on previous 5 stops) saw 1st 4'' lizard, flycatcher here, dragonflies and 2 deer crossing stream.
More stream flow (algae) more insects, lizards.
No running water, steeper drop, cliffs.
Dry streambed. Fewer sycamores.
A cabin to the south.
5 deer crossed creek.
Summer tanagers
from junipers to oaks
First heard cooing, to confirm ID played one more time and it flew in. Positive ID. Knocked a few times but loud coo calls frequently. Initially thought heard bill clattering too?
Battery died on Ipod.
Technical problems, used IBird app for call, call sound below 100 dc
Forest Service Vehicle interrupted playback after 2nd call
Forest Service Vehicle interrupted playback after 2nd call
Waypoint 75 is the beginning of the actual transect. Next 2 points were done away from drainage then came back to drainage.
Bird called 3 more times while installing recorder. Last at 8:00.
Came into playback. Perched in Ash tree
Four wheelers driving along road.
Four wheelers along road
Several vehicles.
Very noisy in boys camp several vehicles. work noise, loading
Dark bird runshing rufous crowned? dark stripe on both sides, medium tapering beak.
Bird with blue wash. Scrub jay? in ocotillo.
1.24 km before the end.
While looking at bird, heard call that seemed to be coming from location further northeast
Very Aggressive bees between 623 and 625. Made waypoint 624. Hive within 30 meters along the wash. Future groups should detour around.
Paused because car came by.
Another car interruption advised us there was cuckoo "in parking lot"
Gray Hawk
Pair in oak tree, no nest seen. Heard as walking away
Difficulty with speaker and location accessibility may have hindered the survey. More detail on data sheet.
Called after 4th callback ... closer called again.
Hit a fenceline.
Heard three times after 1st call
Heard once after 4th call - possibly same YBCU.
Flew in silently, we waited and it flew out with large dark insect in beak. Flew back to recorded location and called several times, seen a few minutes later with large dragonfly.
Heard callign after first playback. Moved closer, not seen
Flew in from East. Totally silent, cirlced us multiple times. Was very curious but not agressive
Likely same bird as last point
Coo heard after P5 and bird then seen flying in - perched and then flew past us to the east
